   ANGERS, FRANCE, JUL 27-30, 1998},
Organization = {EUCARPIA; European Assoc Res Plant Breeding; INRA Res Ctr, Angers; Inst
   Natl Hort},
Abstract = {Selections and hand pollination to produce intra- and interspecific
   hybrids of Leucospermum have been carried out by the ARC Fynbos Unit
   since 1974, with the releasing of 25 cut flower cultivars since 1979.
   Breeding objectives changed over time from the appearance of the flower
   to production characteristics, such as yield per plant, reaction to
   pruning and production of long stems, and disease resistance. A hand
   pollination technique was developed after morphological studies of the
   stigma grove. Initially only pure species were used for hybridisation,
   but since 1986 hybrids was introduced. Hybridisation results are
   unpredictable and can differ from one season to another on the same
   crosses. Two protocols are being used to evaluate the seedlings and the
   clonal material. To develop and release a cultivar can take 19 to 33
   years of selection, propagation and evaluation.},
