   BELGIUM, JUL 03-06, 2001},
Organization = {EUCARPIA},
Abstract = {More than 500 different interspecific cross combinations from 140
   genotypes of 27 Leucadendron species were hand pollinated in 1998-2000
   flowering seasons aiming at producing new cultivars suitable for
   Australian growing conditions. More than 2,000 flower heads were
   collected and about 18,000 seeds were extracted. Over 3,000 seedlings
   representing most cross combinations have been planted. A breeding
   protocol including, selection of parents, pollen collection, assessment
   and storage, isolation of female flowers, pollination and seed
   collection and germination has been developed. Studies of pollen pistil
   interactions revealed that hybridisation barriers exist among some
   interspecific cross combinations. Cytogenetic work indicated that 25
   genotypes involving 15 species studied so far have the same chromosome
   number of 26 with little chromosome size variation.},
